    <exercisegroup>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          In the following exercises, state the type of the quadric surface and describe the trace obtained by intersecting with the given plane. 
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <exercise number="12.6.17">
        <p>
          <m>x^2 + \lp \dfrac{y}{4} \rp^2 + z^2 = 1</m>, <m>\qquad y = 0</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The equation <m>x^2 + \lp \frac{y}{4} \rp^2 + z^2 = 1</m> defines an ellipsoid. 
            The <m>xz</m>-trace is obtained by substituting <m>y = 0</m> in the equation of the ellipsoid. 
            This gives the equation 
            <md>
              x^2 + z^2 = 1
            </md>
            which defines a circle in the <m>xz</m>-plane. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise number="12.6.19">
        <p>
          <m>x^2 + \lp \dfrac{y}{4} \rp^2 + z^2 = 1</m>, <m>\qquad z = \dfrac{1}{4}</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The quadric surface is an ellipsoid, since its equation has the form <m>\lp \frac{x}{a} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{b} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{z}{c} \rp^2 = 1</m> for <m>a = 1</m>, <m>b = 4</m>, and <m>c = 1</m>. 
            To find the trace obtained by intersecting the ellipsoid with the plane <m>z = \frac{1}{4}</m>, we set <m>z = \frac{1}{4}</m> in the equation of the ellipsoid. 
            This gives
            <md>
              <mrow> x^2 + \lp \frac{y}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{1}{4} \rp^2 = 1 </mrow>
              <mrow> x^2 + \frac{y^2}{16} \amp= \frac{15}{16} </mrow>
            </md>
            To get the standard form we divide by <m>\frac{15}{16}</m> to obtain
            <md>
              <mrow> \frac{x^2}{\frac{15}{16}} + \frac{y^2}{\frac{16\cdot 15}{16}} \amp= 1 </mrow>
              <mrow> \implies \qquad \lp \frac{x}{\frac{\sqrt{15}}{4}} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{\sqrt{15}} \rp^2 \amp= 1 </mrow>
            </md>
            We conclude that the trace is an ellipse on the <m>xy</m>-\plane with the equation above. 
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

