      <exercise number="12.6.29">
        <p>
          <m>x^2 + y^2 - z^2 = 1</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The equation defines a hyperboloid of one sheet. 
            The trace on the plane <m>z = z_0</m> is the circle
            <md>
              x^2 + y^2 = 1 + z_0^2
            </md>
            The trace on the plane <m>y = y_0</m> is the hyperbola
            <md>
              x^2 - z^2 = 1 - y_0^2
            </md>
            and the trace on the plane <m>x = x_0</m> is the hyperbola
            <md>
              y^2 - z^2 = 1 - x_0^2
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            We obtain the surface shown below.
          </p>
          
          <figure>
            <caption>The hyperboloid with equation <m>x^2 + y^2 - z^2 = 1</m>.</caption>
            <sidebyside width="80%">
              <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('u, v')
                  
                  # 1. Set fixed dimensions for x^2 + y^2 - z^2 = 1
                  # In this specific case, a=1, b=1, c=1
                  a, b, c = 1, 1, 1
                  
                  # 2. Define Parametric Equations
                  # x = a*cosh(u)cos(v), y = b*cosh(u)sin(v), z = c*sinh(u)
                  # We restrict u to -1.3 to 1.3 to keep the view focused on the center "waist"
                  u_max = 1.3
                  
                  hyperboloid = parametric_plot3d(
                      (a*cosh(u)*cos(v), b*cosh(u)*sin(v), c*sinh(u)),
                      (u, -u_max, u_max), (v, 0, 2*pi),
                      opacity=0.6,
                      color='cyan',
                      mesh=True
                  )
                  
                  # 3. Define Axes and Limits
                  # Calculate how wide the shape gets at the top/bottom to set axis length
                  max_radius = max(a,b) * cosh(u_max)
                  limit = max(max_radius, c*sinh(u_max)) * 1.2
                  
                  axes = arrow3d((-limit,0,0), (limit,0,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,-limit,0), (0,limit,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,0,-limit), (0,0,limit), color='black', width=1)
                        
                  lbl_axes = text3d("x", (limit+0.2, 0, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("y", (0, limit+0.2, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("z", (0, 0, limit+0.2), color='black', fontweight='bold')

                  # 4. Mark Intercepts at the "Waist" (z=0)
                  # Since this is a one-sheet hyperboloid, it intersects x and y axes at +/- 1
                  pt_size = 15
                  offset = 0.2
                  
                  pts = point3d([(a,0,0), (-a,0,0), (0,b,0), (0,-b,0)], size=pt_size, color='black')
                  
                  lbls = text3d("1",  (a+offset, 0, 0),   color='black', fontsize=20) + \
                        text3d("-1", (-a-offset, 0, 0),  color='black', fontsize=20) + \
                        text3d("1",  (0, b+offset, 0),   color='black', fontsize=20) + \
                        text3d("-1", (0, -b-offset, 0),  color='black', fontsize=20)
                  
                  # 5. Combine and Show
                  show(hyperboloid + axes + lbl_axes + pts + lbls, frame=False)
                </slate>
              </interactive>
            </sidebyside>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise number="12.6.33">
        <p>
          <m>z^2 = \lp \dfrac{x}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \dfrac{y}{8} \rp^2</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            The equation defines an elliptic cone. 
            The trace on the plane <m>z = z_0</m> is the ellipse
            <md>
              \lp \frac{x}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{8} \rp^2 = z_0^2
            </md>
            The trace on the plane <m>y = 0</m> is the hyperbola
            <md>
              z^2 - \lp \frac{x}{4} \rp^2 = 0 \qquad \implies \qquad z = \pm \frac{x}{4}
            </md>
            and the trace on the plane <m>x = 0</m> is the hyperbola
            <md>
              z^2 - \lp \frac{y}{8} \rp^2 = \lp \frac{x_0}{4} \rp^2 \qquad \implies \qquad z = \pm \frac{y}{8}
            </md>
          </p>

          <p>
            The sketch of the surface is shown below.
          </p>

          <figure>
            <caption>The elliptic cone <m>z^2 = \lp \dfrac{x}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \dfrac{y}{8} \rp^2</m>.</caption>
            <sidebyside width="80%">
              <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('u, v')
                  
                  # 1. Define Coefficients
                  # Equation: z^2 = (x/a)^2 + (y/b)^2
                  a, b = 4, 8
                  
                  # 2. Define Parametric Equations for a Cone
                  # x = a*u*cos(v), y = b*u*sin(v), z = u
                  # u represents the height (z-value). 
                  # We range u from negative to positive to show both nappes of the cone.
                  u_max = 1
                  
                  cone = parametric_plot3d(
                      (a*u*cos(v), b*u*sin(v), u),
                      (u, -u_max, u_max), (v, 0, 2*pi),
                      opacity=0.6,
                      color='cyan',
                      mesh=True
                  )
                  
                  # 3. Define Axes and Limits
                  # The widest point is at u_max, where y = b*u_max = 8*1 = 8.
                  limit = max(a*u_max, b*u_max) * 1.2
                  
                  axes = arrow3d((-limit,0,0), (limit,0,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,-limit,0), (0,limit,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,0,-limit), (0,0,limit), color='black', width=1)
                        
                  lbl_axes = text3d("x", (limit+0.5, 0, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("y", (0, limit+0.5, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("z", (0, 0, limit+0.5), color='black', fontweight='bold')

                  # 4. Mark Reference Points
                  # The cone meets at the origin.
                  # To visualize the scale (4 and 8), we mark points on the rim at z=1.
                  pt_size = 10
                  
                  # Origin
                  pts = point3d((0,0,0), size=15, color='black')
                  
                  # Points at z=1 to show the ellipse dimensions
                  # At z=1: x extends to +/- 4, y extends to +/- 8
                  pts += point3d([(a,0,1), (-a,0,1), (0,b,1), (0,-b,1)], size=pt_size, color='blue')
                  
                  # Labels for the reference points
                  offset = 0.5
                  lbls = text3d("4",   (a+offset, 0, 1),   color='black') + \
                        text3d("-4",  (-a-offset, 0, 1),  color='black') + \
                        text3d("8",   (0, b+offset, 1),   color='black') + \
                        text3d("-8",  (0, -b-offset, 1),  color='black') + \
                        text3d("z=1", (a/2, b/2, 1.2),    color='black', fontsize=10)
                  
                  # 5. Combine and Show
                  show(cone + axes + lbl_axes + pts + lbls, frame=False, aspect_ratio=1)
                </slate>
              </interactive>
            </sidebyside>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise number="12.6.39">
        <p>
          <m>x = 1 + y^2 + z^2</m>
        </p>

        <solution>
          <p>
            This is the equation of an elliptic paraboloid oriented along the <m>x</m>-axis.
          </p>

          <p>
            The graph of the surface is shown below. 
          </p>

          <figure>
            <caption>The circular paraboloid <m>x = 1 + y^2 + z^2</m>.</caption>
            <sidebyside width="80%">
              <interactive platform="sage" width="100%" aspect="1:1">
                <slate surface="sage">
                  var('u, v')
                  
                  # 1. Define Parametric Equations
                  # The surface is x = 1 + r^2. Let u = r (radius in yz-plane).
                  # x = 1 + u^2
                  # y = u * cos(v)
                  # z = u * sin(v)
                  
                  # We range u from 0 to 2. This gives x values from 1 to 5.
                  u_max = 2
                  
                  paraboloid = parametric_plot3d(
                      (1 + u^2, u*cos(v), u*sin(v)),
                      (u, 0, u_max), (v, 0, 2*pi),
                      opacity=0.6,
                      color='cyan',
                      mesh=True
                  )
                  
                  # 2. Define Axes and Limits
                  # The shape extends to x=5, and y,z go to +/- 2.
                  # We set the limit based on the longest dimension (x).
                  limit = (1 + u_max^2) * 1.2
                  
                  axes = arrow3d((0,0,0), (limit,0,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,-limit/2,0), (0,limit/2,0), color='black', width=1) + \
                        arrow3d((0,0,-limit/2), (0,0,limit/2), color='black', width=1)
                        
                  lbl_axes = text3d("x", (limit+0.2, 0, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("y", (0, limit/2+0.2, 0), color='black', fontweight='bold') + \
                            text3d("z", (0, 0, limit/2+0.2), color='black', fontweight='bold')

                  # 3. Mark Key Features
                  # The Vertex is at (1, 0, 0)
                  pt_size = 10
                  pts = point3d((1,0,0), size=15, color='black')
                  
                  # Labels
                  offset = 0.3
                  lbls = text3d("Vertex (1,0,0)", (1, 0, -offset), color='black', fontsize=12)
                  
                  # 4. Combine and Show
                  # We force aspect_ratio=[1,1,1] so the paraboloid doesn't look flattened
                  show(paraboloid + axes + lbl_axes + pts + lbls, frame=False, aspect_ratio=[1,1,1])
                </slate>
              </interactive>
            </sidebyside>
          </figure>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup> 

    <exercise number="12.6.45">
      <p>
        Find the equation of the hyperboloid shown in the following figure. 
      </p>

      <figure>
        <image source="sec126-HW45-Figure.png" width="50%"></image>
      </figure>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The hyperboloid in the figure is of one sheet and the intersections with the planes <m>z = z_0</m> are ellipses. 
          Hence, the equation of the hyperboloid has the form 
          <md>
            \lp \frac{x}{a} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{b} \rp^2 - \lp \frac{z}{c} \rp^2 = 1
          </md>
          Substituting <m>z = 0</m>, we get
          <md>
            \lp \frac{x}{a} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{b} \rp^2 = 1
          </md>
          By the given information this ellipse has <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> intercepts at the points <m>(\pm 2, 0, 0)</m> and <m>(0, \pm 3, 0)</m>, hence <m>a = 4</m> and <m>b = 6</m>. 
        </p>

        <p>
          Substituting in the equation of the hyperbolod, we get
          <md>
            \lp \frac{x}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{6} \rp^2 - \lp \frac{z}{c} \rp^2 = 1
          </md>
          Substituting <m>z = 9</m>, we get
          <md>
            <mrow> \frac{x}{16} + \frac{y}{36} - \frac{9^2}{c^2}  \amp= 1 </mrow>
            <mrow> \frac{x^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{36} \amp= 1 + \frac{81}{c^2} = \frac{c^2 + 81}{c^2} </mrow>
            <mrow> \frac{c^2x^2}{16\lp 81 + c^2 \rp} + \frac{c^2y^2}{36\lp 81 + c^2 \rp} \amp= 1 </mrow>
            <mrow> \lp \frac{x}{\frac{4}{c}\sqrt{81 + c^2}} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{\frac{6}{c}\sqrt{81 + c^2}} \rp^2 \amp= 1 </mrow>
          </md>
          By the given information the following must hold. 
          <md>
            \frac{4}{c} \sqrt{81 + c^2} = 8 \qquad \text{and} \qquad \frac{6}{c}\sqrt{81 + c^2} = 12
          </md>
          which implies that
          <md>
            \frac{\sqrt{81 + c^2}}{c} = 2 \qquad \implies \qquad 81 + c^2 = 4c^2 \qquad \implies \qquad 3c^2 = 81
          </md>
          Thus, <m>c = 3\sqrt{3}</m>, and by substituting back we obtain the following equation
          <md>
            \lp \frac{x}{4} \rp^2 + \lp \frac{y}{6} \rp^2 - \lp \frac{z}{3\sqrt{3}} \rp^2 = 1
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

